3. List 3 real-world use cases where TACACS+ is preferred over RADIUS, and briefly explain why TACACS+ is better suited for each scenario.
=>Enterprise Router/Switch Admin Access: TACACS+ allows per-command authorization (e.g., junior admins can only run "show" commands). Better than RADIUS because it separates auth/authz for fine-grained control.
Data Center Network Device Management: Full packet encryption and TCP reliability suit high-security environments where admin sessions must be protected from eavesdropping.
Compliance-Heavy Industries (Banking/Govt): Detailed per-command accounting and authorization help meet auditing requirements

4. Given a scenario where a user tries to log into a network device but fails authentication, describe how RADIUS and TACACS+ would handle the logging and response differently.<br><br><em><strong>Hint:</strong> Focus on how each protocol manages accounting and command authorization.</em>
=>In a failed login to a network device:

RADIUS: Sends Access-Reject. Accounting logs the attempt (failed login, timestamp, source IP) but offers limited command-level detail since it combines functions. Response is quick (UDP) but less detailed for admin troubleshooting.
TACACS+: Also rejects but provides richer accounting logs (including attempted commands if partial auth occurred). Better separation allows logging exactly where authorization failed. TCP ensures reliable delivery of logs.

TACACS+ gives more forensic value for admin failures.

